ce:section.ce:para:
FTIR analysis was used to investigate further the structure and functionalization of the compounds (Fig. 6
                        ). In TNR spectra, the peaks appearing in the pre-1000 cm−1 region are related to the tensile vibrations of TiO2 
                        [60,61]. In NH2-TNR spectra, which deals with amino silane-modified TiO2, the peak in area 2931 cm−1 is related to the CH bending vibration. The 1630 cm−1 peak is associated with the NH2 group of aminopropyl trimethoxysilane [62]. In the S, N-GQD spectrum, the peak appearing in 1717 cm−1 is related to the acidic carbonyl bonds present in the structure [50,63]. The peaks in areas 1575 cm−1 and 1413 cm−1 are related to the tensile vibrations of CC and CN [50]. In the final spectrum for compound TNR-Co-S, N-GQD, graphene quantum dot peaks cover the peaks related to TiO2. However, the peak of carboxylic acid, which appeared in 1717 cm−1, was shifted to 1627 cm−1, indicating carboxylic group conversion to amide groups and GQD attachment to the surface of functionalized TiO2.
